    <title>Combined summary - NODE_EXT_SERVICES and advertising related services</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T02:06:41.808578+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-August/006448.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The given context covers various email exchanges and discussions between Bitcoin developers regarding the implementation of new features and functionality in Bitcoin Core. One suggestion was to use the existing extension mechanism until service bits start running out, as it provides flexibility and adaptability without affecting the core functions of the system. The importance of proper management and monitoring of service bits usage was emphasized to prevent conflicts or errors in the system.Another proposal was to delegate processing of unknown messages to an external process, allowing a P2P node to be composed of separate programs that are indistinguishable from those provided by Bitcoin Core itself. This idea was supported by several developers, including Jeff Garzik, a core developer and open-source evangelist at BitPay. The discussion also covered topics such as adding categories instead of single bits for autodiscovery of block indexes, the use of ZeroMQ as a lightweight message routing system, and the possibility of having bitcoind listen on a separate port for connections from plugins. Overall, the context highlights the collaborative efforts of Bitcoin developers in improving the functionality and efficiency of the Bitcoin network.The conversation is regarding the use of NODE_EXT_SERVICES bit which is used to advertise the P2P "getextsrv" command to get information about an auxiliary service. The user intends to use it for advertising services that are not part of the P2P protocol itself but run on a different port. However, reserving service bits for those services is not acceptable. In an email exchange between Wladimir and Mike Hearn, the former argued that using services bits to advertise services on a different port than the P2P protocol is not acceptable. He explained that services bits are solely meant for advertising services on the P2P network and this was not open for discussion. Additionally, he noted that using only a bit to find an external service would not be sufficient except in cases where the advertised service had a fixed port. Since even bitcoind does not have a fixed port, there needs to be a mechanism to connect to the external service. This mechanism is provided by the proposed extension.The email conversation is regarding a proposal to advertise external services which are not part of the P2P protocol and run on a different port. Christian Decker argues that this kind of advertisement should not be supported in the P2P protocol as we already have a working mechanism for protocol extensions in the P2P network (service flags). Wladimir says that a bit is not enough to find an external service except in cases where the advertised service would have a fixed port.In another conversation, the discussion is about adding categories (classes) instead of a single bit for autodiscovery of block indexes in Bitcoin Wallet for Android. Currently, the app has a hard-coded block explorer, which limits decentralization. However, autodiscovery would take too long, and users would not want to wait for it. By implementing API-based categories of service bits, the process can be made faster and more efficient.The proposal of implementing an external application or script like 'getutxos' could be useful for adding other services like -txindex or nLockTime storage facility into bitcoind. However, this would require a local interprocess message bus for bitcoind. A better alternative would be to use './bitcoind -servicecookie= -allowextservices=127.0.0.1/8' and connect to bitcoind as normal. This will allow any program to send "registersrv" with the cookie and a list of command ids it's interested in, maybe a service bit to set, and start receiving those messages wrapped in a new structure that gives some kind of client ID (like IP address).Lastly, the given context talks about ZeroMQ, a lightweight message routing system that could work as a plug-in by registering internal signals. It aims to capture precise points where a block was accepted internally. ZeroMQ could make P2P messages available to other applications if they subscribe to them and vice versa.</summary>
